{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522769"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13844"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13844"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.04,0.01,0.17,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36882"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"2392"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45270"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of pain and swelling in her right index finger. She denies any recent trauma or insect bites. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her right index finger is swollen, warm, and tender to touch, particularly at the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint. There is reduced range of motion due to pain and swelling. The rest of her joints appear normal. An image of her hand is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Synovitis","Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Septic arthritis","Gout"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image and clinical description are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esynovitis\u003C/strong\u003E of the right index finger, particularly affecting the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint. Synovitis is characterised by inflammation of the synovial membrane lining the joint, resulting in swelling, warmth, tenderness, and reduced range of motion. In this case, the isolated involvement of a single MCP joint in an otherwise healthy individual suggests an acute, localised process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with symmetric polyarthritis, frequently affecting the MCP joints. While it can cause synovitis, the single joint involvement and acute onset in this case make rheumatoid arthritis less likely as the primary diagnosis, though it should remain in the differential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a degenerative joint disease that usually develops gradually over time. It typically affects weight-bearing joints and the distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers. The acute onset and significant swelling of the MCP joint seen in this case are not characteristic of osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E can cause acute, severe joint inflammation but most commonly affects the first metatarsophalangeal joint (big toe). While gout can affect MCP joints, it is less common, and the presentation would typically be more dramatically painful and red.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious condition caused by joint infection. While it can present with similar symptoms to synovitis, septic arthritis usually causes more severe systemic symptoms such as fever and malaise. The patient\u0027s well appearance and normal vital signs make septic arthritis less likely, though it should remain in the differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of synovitis in this case is based on the acute onset, localised swelling, and tenderness of a single MCP joint. Further investigation would be warranted to determine the underlying cause, which could include early rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, crystal arthropathy, or reactive arthritis. Management would typically involve rest, ice, anti-inflammatory medications, and addressing any identified underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Synovitis of the finger joints is characterised by swelling, tenderness, and reduced range of motion.","Metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint synovitis can be caused by various conditions including rheumatoid arthritis, infection, and trauma.","Differential diagnosis of isolated MCP joint synovitis includes rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, gout, and reactive arthritis."],"references":["Dallos T, Oppl B, Kovacs L, et al. Pachydermodactyly: A Review. Curr Rheumatol Rep 2014; 16:442-49"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36882"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13844"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20793"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20793"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D6mcKBJlHrnfRGQoL80mv9ZvSWJ32l.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D6mcKBJlHrnfRGQoL80mv9ZvSWJ32l.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36882"},"attributes":{"crea